    <summary>Designer for labels, business cards and barcodes (unofficial Windows build of gLabels 4)</summary>
    <description><![CDATA[
gLabels is a program for creating labels and business cards. It is designed to work with the
sheets of peel-off labels and card stock sold in office supply shops, and ships a template
database covering more than thirty vendors including Avery, Herma, Zweckform and Dymo.

Text, images, lines, shapes and barcodes can be placed on a label, and a document-merge
feature fills them from a CSV file or address book, so a whole sheet can be personalised in
one pass. Barcode support covers the built-in glbarcode++ symbologies plus zint and
libqrencode. A command line renderer, `glabels-batch-qt`, produces PDFs without opening the
interface.

## About this package

Note on the name: the `glabels` package id belongs to an unrelated 2020 submission that
was never approved and has been dormant since. This package is published as `glabels-qt`,
matching the upstream project's own name.

This is an **unofficial community build**. gLabels 4 (`glabels-qt`) is cross-platform and
builds cleanly on Windows, but the project publishes no Windows binaries, so this package
installs a build compiled from unmodified upstream sources by a public GitHub Actions
workflow:

* Build automation and full logs: https://github.com/ibsorn/glabels-windows
* Upstream project: https://github.com/j-evins/glabels-qt

It is not produced or endorsed by the gLabels authors. Please report **application** bugs to
the upstream tracker and **packaging** problems to the tracker linked above.

## Status

gLabels 4 has no final release yet, so this packages a snapshot of upstream's `master`
branch. It is usable, but treat it as pre-release software and keep backups of your projects.
Every build runs the upstream unit tests, renders a PDF from the packaged tree, and installs
and uninstalls itself on a clean machine before it is published.
]]></description>
